<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-06-20T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-06-20T12:00:00-05:00" n="52" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">821.6363 Barco/586: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-06-20T13:00:00-04:00">June 20, 1931—1
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>44. Legation’s 84, June 18, 2 p.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d52fn27">Not
                                printed.</note> When the Catatumbo contract has been signed<note n="28" xml:id="d52fn28">President Olaya signed the bill approving
                                the Catatumbo contract on June 20, 1931 (821.6363 Barco/592).</note>
                            you may, if in your opinion such action would be helpful and would not
                            be misconstrued, express informally to President Olaya the gratification
                            with which this Government has learned of the final satisfactory
                            solution of this troublesome and longstanding problem.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>